===Etymology===
''Chocolate'' is most often said to come from {{Nahu.}} ''xocolatl'' (e.g. AHD 2000) or ''[[chocolatl]]'' (e.g. Dictionary.com 2006), which would be derived from ''[[xococ]]'' "bitter" and ''[[atl]]'' "water" (with an irregular change of x > ch). Dakin and Wichmann (2000) propose that the ''chocol-'' element refers to special wooden stick used to prepare chocolate.

However, the form ''xocolatl'' is not directly attested, and ''chocolatl'' does not appear in Nahuatl until the mid-18th century, which may indicate another origin. The word may come instead from a {{Mayan.}} language.

In any case, the word ''chocolate'' reached English via {{S.}}.

